The paper focuses on incentive mechanisms for mobile crowdsensing, which involves human users competing for sensing tasks based on their respective costs and available time periods. This suggests that the paper may belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) or Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper deals with scheduling and optimization, which are common topics in the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) and Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. Finally, the paper proposes approximation mechanisms and conducts simulations, which are also relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
